[{"id":26913,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a09b4d85-9559-4099-adcf-2af630d560ea-image.png\" style=\"width: 69px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1999421e-9a8e-4a11-afa7-435b9b3fd4f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 151px; height: 130px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1c6629c5-e045-41cf-83df-137d92371d83-image.png\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7e493045-2ddb-4bbc-8c32-066013854452-9706258_D.png\" style=\"width: 142px; height: 174px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e4a2e435-1f1c-4b50-bb5a-98f3ed2e3e7e-Solution.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 347px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26868,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/328f09fc-61b3-44da-94b4-d656398576a2.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 141px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6e1f29a6-8fdd-42bf-9499-2aea51df74b3.png\" style=\"width: 205px; height: 176px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f522d948-d7d0-4393-b529-0d4a3696d38b.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 128px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dfd015e9-fd3f-4bb5-8d94-6e0d35e357b1.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 144px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Aldehydes and ketones react with water to give 1,1-geminal diols known as hydrates. In general, hydrates are not stable enough to be isolated as the equilibrium shifts back to starting materials (due to Le Chatelier&#39;s principle). But the following ketone forms stable diol due to the formation hydrogen bonding as shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e7165f81-3458-45ac-b5d7-ea10f9e48708.png\" style=\"width: 380px; height: 194px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26841,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/vfzXi3Yeeax5FNlrdClwwjc0bCjnDbfdB5qfQoF4n0I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n0.1 mole of compound ( S ) weight in gm\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& =0.1 \\times \\text { molar mass of compound }(\\mathrm{S}) \\\\\n& =0.1 \\times 130=13 \\mathrm{gm}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26825,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["5","2","4","3"],"answer":2,"solution":"In acetylation, each hydroxyl group reacts:<br>R-OH + (CH₃CO)₂O → R-O-CO-CH₃ + CH₃COOH.<br>Each -OH is converted to -OCOCH₃, resulting in a net mass increase of 42 g/mol per hydroxyl group (addition of acetyl group mass 43, removal of hydrogen mass 1).<br>Given: Original molar mass = 122 g/mol, Product molar mass = 290 g/mol<br>Total mass increase = 290 - 122 = 168 g/mol<br>Number of hydroxyl groups = 168 ÷ 42 = 4","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26869,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3bb12f82-7c92-42fe-8e34-a79e852a6435.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 189px;\" />","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9177679-a55e-4280-ba32-9388f7d12b45.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 203px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5917c281-18e4-465c-8d71-266b4928ee4b.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 180px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e710fd58-3e4b-452e-a059-c0efe2f7c49e.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 198px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In the first step protonation of alcohol takes place which leads to the formation of carbocation. Ring expansion takes place in the next step. In the given process five membered ring&nbsp;become six membered ring. Now, the carbocation loses proton in the presence of potassium hydroxide to give alkene.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1843ca9-36f0-4d42-80a1-91fe5bc5640c.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 490px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26882,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["a &gt; d &gt; b &gt; c","b &gt; d &gt; c &gt; a","b &gt; a &gt; d &gt; c","d &gt; b &gt; c &gt; a"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The dehydration of alcohol takes place via the formation of a&nbsp;carbocation. Hence, the rate of reaction depends on the stability of carbocation.</p><p>No dehydration is possible in phenol because carbocation formation is difficult in case of phenol.</p><p>Option (d) fast due to loss of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;conjugation increasing stable of compound as compared to (c). Option(b) is very fast because stable compound formed.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26919,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are true."],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>Mixture of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is called water gas or syn gas<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>Syn gas is produced by coal gasification <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><mn>1270</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow></mover><mi>CO</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26942,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2609148b-0086-4ce8-a16a-29b12b5ee41b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e531d14c-6e92-49dc-8d6b-00836c4b8d4c-image.png\" style=\"width: 224px; height: 80px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/09840c42-68af-465b-8e05-bc9063ff89e1-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9615fb4b-3ea0-46cc-9f8f-b9c40a703098-image.png\" style=\"width: 189px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15ef69b9-0f06-425f-806f-57487f22f9a9-image.png\" style=\"width: 357px; height: 288px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26969,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79b00191-f76c-4846-aebf-1ee539c280d5-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 175px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/86dfe64d-5152-40bf-9c24-96a89f08bb7c-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 173px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8c2a7c32-4c61-4d1d-aae2-da2f2d427590-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 141px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3d1b0978-ff8f-4743-8034-97c64390c664-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 179px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f9160b2-f2ec-4463-b066-aeb1fe2ed28c-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 259px;\" />Methoxy group increases the pKa of the phenol group - it makes it less acidic. The oxygen atom does indeed exert an electron-withdrawing inductive effect, but the lone pairs on the oxygen cause the exact opposite effect So the methoxy group is an electron-donating group by resonance.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e64b9a3a-a36e-47e3-aa42-57a21d05404a-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 309px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26839,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0OysscCR70UVRM7lgL6zfe5cjnl6Vbnw_dExYi6U57c.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/iiErfwUmZcJVaDvZOJQdxwHBp_Ic5tYyrljWcSI75qA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Tz3S-uachaYcxYGyZMAkp8XMC8LsjixhG6FoawmsVMc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GCAX5lPGOTZDLfnPeLWEmIJ3Qip0rzKdEN5Tzh5AOow.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0A2gDcH2nP2C5WuGWWBHicWn7z7nCwuzffQ4MVPHQoM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26996,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Rate of reaction will be slow due to slow cleavage of carbon-halogen bond.","Alkene will be the main product.","Simple ether will form instead of mixed ether.","Expected mixed ether will be formed."],"answer":1,"solution":"The tertiary alkyl halide undergo elimination reaction to give alkenes\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/iwwruheRKnzmYkV1Z3uJnWbqBcypfmbHiXzs8-i2fTY.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Q5keBSCu7a1m5VBDi9fIqciQhiJE5qzP2DqdYC5bkjI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26856,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oL2DDJfQP71cwW4b4Mj3GAzAWtQM548SK9wtoQfXzdw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nEZ3HH1Zou56fbyAx7qmC5RdERgn0MnjgpnUv0dEbCU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Y7apY4dxjqPakxFW-AQ2uDCpsHaCSM8HYslctij1U5Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4D3sKv0l1EiBNKTYfA_s--zGt4O1mmRkG5NjIr0dMxM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/NbXXYyLT5M7FsVyfNC_r_1bvXXBzn8qb-etdLCRYo0o.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26978,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["2, 4, 6 - Trinitrophenol","Benzene sulphonic acid","o - Nitrophenol","Benzoic acid"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">o-Nitrophenol is insoluble in sodium hydrogen carbonate because it is less acidic than carbonic acid.While, others being more acidic than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;dissolve in sodium bi&nbsp;carbonate.</p><p>&nbsp;Hence, the given&nbsp;reaction will not be spontaneous.&nbsp;<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0026256DUP02HIN1.JPG\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 98px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26947,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/77ddda70-de57-4af8-9ca9-cf3aaa2b43e6-image.png\" style=\"width: 127px; height: 89px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/569378bb-4a27-4954-b7a2-17073563a7ad-image.png\" style=\"width: 142px; height: 97px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/41c52cc3-d9a3-4fe1-90de-68b7d2243fc2-image.png\" style=\"width: 157px; height: 92px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/648633bf-5c21-4229-a715-7ec2f847049e-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 92px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ab73af6-3638-4837-aec4-f0fb8ba6cf04-image.png\" style=\"width: 548px; height: 218px;\" />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26998,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Secondary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>2","Tertiary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>2","Secondary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>1","Tertiary alcohol by S<sub>N</sub>1"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>3&deg;&nbsp;alcohol reacts fastest giving white turbidity immediately on adding Lucas reagent.<br />Reaction takes place through carbocation formation involving S<sub>N</sub><sup>1</sup>&nbsp;mechanism.&nbsp;Rate of reaction in this reaction is directly proportional to the stability of the carbocation formed.<br />3&deg;&nbsp;R-OH(tertiary alcohol) forms 3&deg;&nbsp;carbocation and therefore, the&nbsp;reaction is fastest.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/389d19f9-0233-4330-a80a-0b91361c4042-image.png\" style=\"width: 648px; height: 170px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26985,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">3</mi></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">3</mi></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">3</mi></msub><msub><mi>CHOHCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COH</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/25990ss.png\" style=\"width: 372px; height: 64px;\" /></p><p>According to the question, The hydroboration oxidation reaction is an organic chemical reaction which is employed for the conversion of alkenes into alcohols that are neutral. This is done via a&nbsp;two-step process which includes a hydroboration step and an oxidation step<em><strong>.</strong></em></p><p>&nbsp;Hydroboration oxidation reaction&nbsp;is a two-step&nbsp;reaction&nbsp;in which alkene reacts with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, THF (tetrahydrofuran) and hydrogen peroxide in a basic medium to give alcohol. This is done by a net addition (across the entire double bond) of water.</p><p>Hydroboration oxidation&nbsp;reaction mechanism can be considered as an<span style=\"color:null;\">&nbsp;anti-markovnikov</span><span style=\"color:null;\">&nbsp;r</span>eaction where a hydroxyl group attaches itself to the carbon which is less substituted.</p><p>So, according to this reaction, propene give <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math>-propyl-alcohol.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26904,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ec7e1d96-f673-476c-a76e-8ec052fbe76d-9754537.png\" style=\"width: 430px; height: 183px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;It is a colorless liquid with a piercing, acrid smell. The smell of burnt fat (as when cooking oil is heated to its smoke point) is caused by glycerol in the burning fat breaking down into acrolein. It does not have fruity smell so, statement II&nbsp;is incorrect.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26852,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4H6ls5uDi078n8XR6s_daSbfir3TUrwUsq0w5Lti_f8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/O6qf_tLMBf8sxt5v6_tleQzCh-4Ps4XoqMjpNk0MZk8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EeUymD8AmemYoUtd5MTApSnUpVKABPdb8ECIaa3vvdQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ql8MmLk46Iaf-z0W0t26t5YdzH5GDe9L0yLWHvn97Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kzAmFBeK7yHb2zLbNGEtCfJejUnCyBAp1rL0AarTO7s.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26968,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/G3I_qztiRalrYTWYP8hWiUOgGSqh5DlgxHmOKkuWIJI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DGD1QYes-bktrIxakFtOtkvufWj5cq2Wj-zsivJb1rs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9gX327pWDs0hYu036ngj1uWeWh1AZlioCXWJohTN4aQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a_FSue41izi_p7XHEH1jbeVBaEA13vNqYZ2xe6UtRHY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"PCC oxidizes primary alcohols to aldehydes and secondary alcohols to ketones. In the above reaction, $-\\mathrm{OCOCH}_3$ group is hydrolyzed to secondary alcohol which is then oxidised (with PCC) to ketone.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66X9UgV841OAOmjVsJtRKrEunek4_hx9QfBXqxFszyk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/OOLq4pp8pW8f9gUbEIh6JzRECku20bdFQg1xT5sJQUs.rendered.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":26926,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21d5dade-b4f3-452d-8315-0cd5ec713568-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3bed017f-d709-4157-b11b-7fd432bf86e5-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 131px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8d329932-8f83-409b-84b1-1b91a65ef1fd-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 108px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e271fb0-66fc-4aec-9a03-1b4103a311b6-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 120px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img height=\"333\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d123de49-53b7-4087-b418-d07d3a1a68be-image.png\" width=\"501\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26855,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":2,"solution":"Phenol is a highly activated compound which can undergo bromination directly with Bromine without any lewis acid.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26884,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The given compound not dissolve in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cold</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>NaHCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NaOH</mi></math> solution, means&nbsp; that does not have&nbsp;carboxylic acid group or&nbsp;phenol group.&nbsp; But&nbsp;the compounds will dissolve in hot <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> solution means they contain&nbsp;ester functional group.</p><p>The compounds <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>7</mn></math>&nbsp;contain ester functional group.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26843,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement I is correct as boiling point of alcohol phenols increase with increase in the number of C -atoms due to increase in van der Waals forces.\nStatement II is correct, since alcohols phenols have intermolecular H -bonding therefore their boiling points are higher in comparison to other class of compounds such as ethers, haloalkanes.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26860,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> is a measure of  the acidity of a particular molecule. It measures the strength of an acid by how tightly a proton is held by a Bronsted acid. The lower the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math>, the stronger the acid and the greater its ability to donate its protons. describe the acidity of a particular molecule.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>logK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math></p><p>Hence, Assertion is true,</p><p>Phenol is more acidic than ethanol because after losing a proton <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced></math>, phenol forms phenoxide ion which is stabilised by resonance whereas ethoxide ion is not.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26941,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/72c8b7e3-b05a-4ea3-9e03-42521f22a918-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 127px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d049873f-3a47-47e5-85ad-b60a5d637441-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 128px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f3be53c3-2fde-4067-aa72-bf34f39de434-image.png\" style=\"width: 114px; height: 127px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6379f821-f063-4abc-823f-096db5c5a194-image.png\" style=\"width: 115px; height: 129px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a294475-fd90-4030-96e6-3ac354fb21ba-image.png\" style=\"width: 317px; height: 129px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26886,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["(A), (E),&nbsp;(B), (D), (C)","(A), (B), (E), (D), (C)","(C), (D), (E), (B), (A)","(C), (E), (D), (B), (A)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Order of acidity for following phenol is</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fb4292fe-0b38-48f8-986f-f9b53d93d2c5-9894780.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 146px;\" /></p><p>Increasing order of pK<sub>a</sub>&nbsp;means most acidic will be placed first.&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;groups at ortho and para position increases acidic strength in phenol. Hence, (A) is most acidic.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>, Hyperconjugation,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> decreases K<sub>a&nbsp;</sub>Value of&nbsp;2,4,5-Trimethylphenol. Hence (C), is least acidity.</p><p>So, the order of pK<sub>a</sub> value is (A) &lt; (B )&lt; (E)&lt; (D)&lt; (C).</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26931,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["(b) and (d) only","(a) and (c) only","(b), (c) and (d) only","(a), (b) and (d) only"],"answer":2,"solution":"Bromine water gives tribromo products,&nbsp; other gives monobromo products in which para is major product.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26971,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qwrhmbiwusndfwkmelnimqlipsgnfcudyvqimczmdcvxislkty.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ryhuzgldkqmtansmgkvumtyfzkqyismxxzjbumvttpdrkupidz.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nowcdsreqxolrosuponxohzpvnwxucypqchekhuqeoqxhumdsq.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gstssyvxcsqvgykhstevgykeduzggbfngrhiucuezogczlzbtl.jpeg\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In the first step hydrogen&nbsp;iodide attacks the ether according to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;mechanism and in the second step&nbsp;hydrogen&nbsp;iodide attacks the ether according to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;mechanism.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f311322b-b353-439f-be50-8d8eba5fe446-4ca8ddf6-6360-4944-8142-f0a943ca3581-07cfdce1-ecf7-4edf-a02d-081ff94a23c9-84.jpg\" style=\"width: 498px; height: 237px;\" /><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27000,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["2-Butanol","2-Methylpropan-2-ol","2-Methylpropanol","1-Butanol"],"answer":1,"solution":"$3^{\\circ}$ alcohols react fastest with $\\mathrm{ZnCl}_2 /$ conc. $\\mathrm{HCl}$ due to formation of $3^{\\circ}$ carbocation and\n$\\therefore 2-$ methyl propan-2-ol is the only $3^{\\circ}$ alcohol","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":26911,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d08de57e-17b4-4a01-aa8d-d4eddaa50729-9726782.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 447px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null}]